Cervical Cancer Type 3 and Type 2 image classification using TensorFlow (Transfer Learning), Cloud Machine Learning Engine

Cervical Cancer Type 3 and Type 2 image classification using TensorFlow

We will use BigQuery, DataFlow and Transfer Learning technique and train and host our model on Cloud Machine Learning Engine. This dataset is courtesy of https://www.kaggle.com (Intel Challenge)


Dataset organization

Organize the dataset into two parts:

  1. Upload the images to Google Cloud Storage.
  2. Create a BigQuery table that has two columns: image_url and label. The image_url is the GCS location and the label is the true classification type.

Create bucket



Create a new bucket to hold your model etc. At the end of this lab, you can delete that bucket.













In [44]:



    


bucket = 'gs://' + 'cervical_truncated_images'
preprocessed_dir = bucket + '/preprocessed'
model_dir = bucket + '/model'

import os
os.environ['GCS_BUCKET'] = bucket

 Preprocessing with DataFlow 



Now that we have the images in Cloud Storage and the labels in BigQuery, we can use Datalab's ML Toolbox to do transfer learning. This consists of three steps: (1) Preprocessing (2) Training, and (3) Deploying.













In [ ]:



    


import mltoolbox.image.classification as model
from google.datalab.ml import *
import os

train_set = BigQueryDataSet("SELECT image_url, label FROM demos.cervical_truncated_images")

preprocess_job = model.preprocess_async(train_set, preprocessed_dir, cloud={'num_workers': 30})
preprocess_job.wait()

 Training 



Train the last few layers of the inception model based on our images.













In [16]:



    


import mltoolbox.image.classification as model
from google.datalab.ml import *
job = model.train_async(preprocessed_dir, 64, 5000, model_dir,  # batchsize, numsteps
                  cloud=CloudTrainingConfig('us-central1', 'BASIC_GPU'))
























Job "image_classification_train_170803_034015" submitted.
Click here to view cloud log. 



















In [45]:



    


import mltoolbox.image.classification as model
from google.datalab.ml import *
model_dir = bucket + '/model_BASIC'
job = model.train_async(preprocessed_dir, 64, 5000, model_dir,  # batchsize, numsteps
                  cloud=CloudTrainingConfig('us-central1', 'BASIC'))
























Job "image_classification_train_170803_202224" submitted.
Click here to view cloud log. 

























Wait for the above job to complete before proceeding to next step (monitor job progress on the GCP console under ML Engine | Jobs).  It should take about 15 minutes to complete.

Stopped TensorBoard with pid 30530

























When I did it, I got 73% accuracy on the held-out (evaluation dataset). This is not bad considering that we started with just few images!




 Deploy and predict model 



Deploy the trained model as a web service. This simply a short cut to the underlying gcloud commands.













In [18]:



    


Models().create('cervical_cancer_truncated_screening')
ModelVersions('cervical_cancer_truncated_screening').deploy('v1', model_dir)
























Waiting for operation "projects/indigo-bloom-118922/operations/create_cervical_cancer_truncated_screening_v1-1501777181764"
Done.

























Once the model is deployed, we can send along an image and we will get back the classification probabilities. (these images are not among the 200 or so images used in training or in evaluation)
